{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CdH8E4eguP8uciPePbgMQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Fixed. All 3 tests pass, including the new regression test.\n\n**The bug:** In `src/validate.js`, the domain pattern for middle labels was `(\\.[A-Za-z0-9-]*)*` — the `*` on the character class allowed a label to be *empty*. So a lone `.` in `mail..example.com` matched as a dot followed by an empty label, and validation accepted it.\n\n**The fix:** Changed `*` to `+` so every dot-separated label must have at least one character:\n\n```js\n/^[^\\s@]+@[A-Za-z0-9-]+(\\.[A-Za-z0-9-]+)*\\.[A-Za-z]{2,}$/\n```\n\nThis matches the intent already documented in the comment (\"Labels must be NON-EMPTY — consecutive dots are invalid\"). `user@mail..example.com` now correctly returns `false`, while normal addresses like `ada@example.com` still pass."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":448,"cache_read_input_tokens":23914,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":448},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d96ae0db-c50c-478c-9ae9-410af39b1b6b","uuid":"0c1abc6b-86e5-4938-90bd-74ed0edb7fab","timestamp":"2026-07-22T12:50:50.285Z","request_id":"req_011CdH8E3BPTRgpHmTtKS4sV"}
